# Vector Calculus

## Introduction
A field is 

### Scalar Field
A scalar field is a function of a space whose value at each point is a scalar quantity (ie. magnitude only).

Examples:
Height Map, Temperature Map

### Vector Field
A vector field is a function of a space whose value at each point is a vector quantity (ie. direction and magnitude).

Examples:
Wind Map



## Basics
For ease of understanding, it is first easiest to understand vector calculus in cartesian coordinates. Consider for now that $ \nabla $ is the vector operator:

$$ \nabla = \begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial y} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\
\end{pmatrix} $$

### Gradient
$$ \nabla f $$
$$ \nabla f = \begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \\
\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \\
\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}
\end{pmatrix} $$
Vector Operator -> Vector

### Divergence
$$ \nabla \cdot \underline{f} $$
Scalar Operator -> Scalar

Div = 0 - Solenoidal = Incompressible 
 
### Curl
$$ \nabla \times \underline{f} $$
Vector Operator -> Vector

Curl = 0 - Conservative = Irrotational

### Laplacian
$$ \nabla^{2}f $$
$$ \nabla \cdot (\nabla f) $$
$$ \nabla^{2} f = \begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial^{2} f}{\partial x^{2}} +
\frac{\partial^{2} f}{\partial y^{2}} +
\frac{\partial^{2} f}{\partial z^{2}}
\end{pmatrix} $$

Scalar Operator -> Scalar

